Plantation, a city residing comfortably within [Broward County](/Broward_County,_Florida), [Florida](/Florida), is an integral component of the sprawling [South Florida metropolitan area](/South_Florida_metropolitan_area). The city's rather evocative name, a topic of some recent discussion, is derived from its former partial owner, the Everglades Plantation Company. This company's early, and ultimately quite futile, endeavors involved establishing a rice [plantation](/Plantation_complexes_in_the_Southern_United_States) in an area that, as history would repeatedly demonstrate, had other plans. As of the [2020 US census](/2020_United_States_census), the population of this ever-developing locale stood at a respectable 91,750, a testament to its persistent growth despite its challenging origins.

## History

The history of Plantation is a fascinating, if sometimes frustrating, tale of human ambition clashing with the relentless realities of nature. It's a narrative woven with grand visions, financial gambles, and a fair share of watery setbacks.

### Land acquisition and drainage (1855–1930)

Before the dawning of the 20th century, the very ground upon which Plantation now stands was an indistinguishable part of the vast, indifferent expanse of [Everglades](/Everglades) wetlands. This primordial landscape, with a certain stubborn insistence, remained regularly submerged under two to three feet of water [^7]. It was hardly an ideal canvas for urban development, but then again, that rarely stops anyone.

In 1855, the [Florida](/Florida) state legislature, in a move that would set the stage for much future drama, enacted the Internal Improvement Act. This legislation brought into existence the Internal Improvement Trust Fund, a governmental agency whose trustees were tasked with the seemingly straightforward duties of overseeing the management, sale, and subsequent development of state-owned land [^8] [^9] [^10]. Fast forward to 1897, when the [Interior Department](/United_States_Department_of_the_Interior) optimistically submitted a claim for 2.9 million acres to the Florida Land Office. However, this grand submission was swiftly revoked the following year, largely due to legitimate concerns that such an appropriation might "impinge upon the rights and interests of the [Seminole](/Seminole) Tribes" [^8]. And rightly so, as the Seminole people had long considered this very area their own, utilizing it regularly for critical activities such as hunting, fishing, and camping. Furthermore, the nearby [Pine Island Ridge](/Pine_Island_Ridge,_Florida) served as a strategic headquarters for them during the tumultuous second and third [Seminole Wars](/Seminole_Wars) [^7].

The narrative of transformation truly began in 1899, when Florida Governor [William Sherman Jennings](/William_Sherman_Jennings) initiated an ambitious, some might say audacious, campaign to drain the [Everglades](/Everglades). To firmly establish Florida's claim to this vast, watery expanse, Jennings secured a new patent, famously known as the 'Everglades Patent,' for land "aggregating 2,862,280 acres" [^8]. His successor, [Napoleon Bonaparte Broward](/Napoleon_B._Broward), who was elected in 1905, enthusiastically continued this drainage initiative, a theme that had, perhaps predictably, been central to his election campaign. Broward, upon taking office, promptly appointed Jennings as general counsel of the Internal Improvement Fund. He then went on to describe the monumental task of [drainage](/Drainage) not merely as an opportunity, but as a solemn duty of the trustees, promising with a flourish to create an "Empire of the Everglades" [^11] [^8] [^7]. A rather grandiloquent vision that likely sounded more impressive in a campaign speech than it ever did in reality.

The initial, somewhat tentative, attempts to drain the [Everglades](/Everglades) commenced in 1906. This involved the construction and subsequent launching of two formidable [dredges](/Dredging) into the nascent [New River](/New_River_(Broward_County,_Florida)). The first, christened 'The Okeechobee' and under the command of Captain Walter S. Holloway of the esteemed [US Army Corps of Engineers](/United_States_Army_Corps_of_Engineers), began its work by cutting from the river's south fork, thereby initiating the creation of the South New River Canal. Simultaneously, 'The Everglades' commenced its relentless cutting from the north fork, pushing northward towards the expansive [Lake Okeechobee](/Lake_Okeechobee), thus giving birth to the North New River Canal [^8] [^12] [^7]. It is worth noting that the very first waterway to emerge from these Herculean drainage efforts was aptly named The Holloway Canal, a fitting tribute to Captain Holloway's pioneering efforts [^7].

Following a rather consequential meeting at the [1908 Democratic National Convention](/1908_Democratic_National_Convention), Governor Broward and Jennings brokered a significant deal with a character named [Richard 'Dicky' J. Bolles](/Richard_%22Dicky%22_J._Bolles). This agreement saw the fund trustees grant Bolles a staggering 500,000 acres (2,000 km^2^) of state lands that were, at the time, perpetually "overflowed." The price? A seemingly modest $2 per acre. Critically, the deal stipulated that 50% of the resultant $1 million in proceeds would be exclusively dedicated to drainage and reclamation efforts. A further agreement committed to the establishment of five major canals. Bolles, capitalizing on this windfall, then founded the Florida Fruit Lands Company, effectively becoming the [Everglades](/Everglades)' first truly private developer [^8] [^13] [^14]. One might say he saw opportunity where others only saw swamp.

The Everglades Plantation Company itself was formally established in January 1909. This came after Adam A. Boggs, an astute attorney and vice president of the Miami Bank and Trust Company, and A.B. Sanders, an engineer who would later ascend to the presidency of the Miami Engineering and Construction Company, entered into a two-year contract with the Internal Improvement Fund trustees. Their stated ambition was to establish a rice [plantation](/Plantations_in_the_American_South) within the [Everglades](/Everglades) [^15] [^16]. The terms of this agreement afforded Boggs & Sanders the ability to rent a substantial tract of land strategically located around the (then still very much a work-in-progress) North New River Canal. Furthermore, they secured the option to subsequently purchase this land at a variable rate of between $3 and $15 per acre [^15].

It later emerged, with a certain predictable irony, that the land leased to Boggs & Sanders already rightfully belonged to Dicky Bolles, being part of the original 500,000 acres he had previously acquired. Despite Bolles's vociferous claims, the Everglades Plantation Company managed to retain control of the land [^15]. Sanders, undeterred, spearheaded further reclamation efforts in the area, which included the rather extensive excavation of 60 miles of ditches [^15]. Boggs & Sanders were also granted successive extensions to their initial two-year contract, a necessary concession given the persistent, and rather inconvenient, fact that the land stubbornly remained underwater [^15].

In 1911, Bolles, ever the entrepreneur, orchestrated a land lottery, grandly dubbed the Progresso Land Auction. Lots were offered at $20–24 per acre, promising residential plots within the grandly named Town of Progresso (an area now more prosaically known as [Wilton Manors](/Wilton_Manors,_Florida)) to anyone who purchased five acres or more of farmland in the drainage zone [^17] [^18] [^19]. However, the promised auction never actually materialized, and, in a recurring theme, the purchased land remained obstinately submerged. This led, quite inevitably, to a lawsuit being filed against Bolles [^13] [^20].

The year 1912 marked a significant milestone with the official opening of the North New River Canal [^8]. Complementing this, the Sewell Lock (also known, rather unglamorously, as Lock No.1) was constructed just outside what would eventually become Plantation. This lock, a pioneering feat of engineering and one of the oldest remaining structures within [Broward County](/Broward_County,_Florida), facilitated crucial water access between the vast [Everglades](/Everglades) and [Lake Okeechobee](/Lake_Okeechobee) [^21] [^22] [^7].

The aforementioned lawsuit against Bolles was finally settled in November 1913. The outcome saw Bolles retain the $1.4 million he had already collected, but he was strictly prohibited from any further collection until the land was demonstrably drained and properly surveyed. Bolles's legal troubles continued, leading to his arrest in December of that year, though he was subsequently acquitted [^13]. A brief moment of accountability, perhaps, before the relentless march of development resumed.

Despite these ambitious efforts, the large-scale drainage of the land largely proved to be a failure. Much of it, with a certain poetic justice, reverted back to the state due to unpaid taxes. However, two local farmers, O. L Daniel and Dewey Hawkins, began systematically acquiring these distressed lands, eventually amassing approximately 6,000 acres and 4,000 acres respectively [^17]. Clearly, some people learn from history, others merely repeat it with slight variations.

In the years following their initial agreement, the contract negotiations between the Everglades Plantation Company and the Internal Improvement Trustees spiraled into protracted legal battles. These disputes finally concluded in 1914, notably in the company's favor. The Trustees, having seemingly learned their lesson about the inherent challenges of rice cultivation in a swamp, no longer insisted on the continuation of the rice plantation attempts. From this point forward, the company wisely shifted its primary focus to the more straightforward, and presumably less waterlogged, business of land sales [^15] [^23].

[Broward County](/Broward_County,_Florida), originally envisioned under the rather fitting name of Everglades County but ultimately named in honor of former governor Broward, was formally established by the [Florida](/Florida) legislature in 1915. Its creation involved the strategic combination of portions of both Dade County and Palm Beach County [^24] [^7].

Fueled by the initial, if somewhat exaggerated, successes of the drainage projects, [Florida](/Florida) experienced a frenetic period known as the [Florida Land Boom](/Florida_land_boom_of_the_1920s) between 1920 and 1925. This era witnessed an unprecedented surge in both population and land sales, a veritable feeding frenzy of speculation and ambition. The boom, like all good speculative bubbles, reached its dizzying peak in the fall of 1925, only to spectacularly collapse in 1926 [^11] [^8].

The land boom's dramatic denouement was swiftly followed by two exceptionally severe hurricanes that hammered the area, leaving widespread devastation in their wake and tragically claiming thousands of lives [^25] [^8]. The first, a formidable storm in September 1926 (now historically known as the [1926 Miami hurricane](/1926_Miami_hurricane)), unleashed terrifying wind speeds of 140 miles per hour. This was followed by another destructive force in September 1928 (the infamous [1928 Okeechobee hurricane](/1928_Okeechobee_hurricane)), which roared through with winds of 135 miles per hour [^8]. In the wake of such natural catastrophes, additional flood control legislation was finally established, and, with a renewed sense of urgency, millions of additional dollars were poured into drainage efforts across the [Everglades](/Everglades) in the subsequent decades. A rather expensive, and often belated, lesson in respecting the power of the natural world.

### Initial development (1931–1952)

Frederick C. Peters, a millionaire heir whose fortunes were rooted in the decidedly less glamorous world of shoe manufacturing, arrived in Goulds, [Florida](/Florida) in 1931. This move was prompted by doctor's advice, urging him to seek a warmer climate for his son's health. Peters, a man of diverse interests, promptly embarked on both potato farming and cattle ranching ventures [^26] [^27] [^7] [^28]. However, by 1939, Peters received counsel from Stephan Zacher, an experienced ranch-owner, who suggested that he would find significantly better land for his cattle in [Davie, Florida](/Davie,_Florida) [^26]. With most large tracts of land in Davie already firmly established as agricultural groves, Peters, after extensive and prudent testing conducted by the [United States Soil Conservation Service](/Natural_Resources_Conservation_Service), eventually purchased a substantial 10,000 acres (40 km^2^) further north. The cost was approximately $10–25 per acre, financed with a hefty $350,000 mortgage [^26] [^28] [^7]. This expansive parcel of land had previously been under the ownership of Dewey Hawkins (who held the majority share) and, with a touch of historical continuity, Boggs' and Sanders' Everglades Plantation Company [^7] [^26].

Peters, harboring a vision (perhaps somewhat quixotic) of forging a farming-cooperative-based, rural alternative, a pastoral counterpoint to the burgeoning suburban sprawl of Dade County, set about constructing the city's inaugural ranch buildings. These structures were thoughtfully designed by Stephan Zacher, the ranch-owner who had initially advised Peters [^26] [^28]. In 1942, he entrusted Leslie E. Bitting, the son of Ben Bitting (who had worked at Peters' previous Dade County farm), with the task of relocating Peters' cattle to this new area and overseeing the ongoing construction [^17].

Between 1944 and 1945, Peters' original concept of a farming cooperative began to evolve, shifting towards a more comprehensive urban design. He enlisted the expertise of acclaimed architect [Russell Pancoast](/Russell_Pancoast) to assist in the creation of a detailed city master plan, and C. Kay Davis to establish a robust water control system [^28] [^7]. Further demonstrating a commitment to managing the area's inherent hydrological challenges, a special-purpose local government, aptly named the Old Plantation Water Control District, was chartered by the state in 1946. Led by civil engineer John Brendla, its mandate was to commence the arduous task of draining the area previously earmarked for plantation development and to diligently oversee its crucial secondary canals [^17] [^29] [^30].

Chauncey Clark Jr., a transplant from Michigan who had been residing in Miami Beach, was presented with an enticing offer by Peters: in exchange for an effective development plan, Peters would provide land options and ensure the necessary drainage and access. Clark Jr.'s initial plan, which envisioned 40-acre ranches, various clubs, golf courses, and even an airfield, regrettably failed to attract the requisite investment. However, his father, Chauncey Clark Sr., proposed an alternative scheme: single-acre lots, each featuring a two-bedroom house and a 20-tree orchard [^26]. Miami's own Robert Law Weed was commissioned to design the first homes, which were subsequently constructed in 1947 on East Acre Drive, under the corporate banner of Plantation Homes Inc. [^26] [^17]. The development's name, 'Plantation,' which would eventually lend itself to the entire city, simply arose from how the area had already become known, including its Water Control District subdivision [^15]. A name, one might observe, that carries a certain historical baggage.

Clark's promotional materials rather optimistically heralded Plantation as "the Dream City," promising "Rich Living at Small Cost." Peters' own advertising echoed this sentiment, proudly declaring "A Full Acre with Every Home" [^17] [^28] [^7]. A two-bedroom home, complete with an acre of land and 20 fruit trees, was offered for $10,241, with the underlying property valued at $200 per acre [^17] [^7]. However, early into the construction phase, many of these nascent homes were tragically destroyed by severe flooding, a consequence of an unrelenting 93 consecutive days of rain, exacerbated by the unwelcome arrival of two hurricanes [^26] [^17] [^31] [^25]. Despite these rather significant setbacks, 15 houses were, remarkably, still under construction when the hurricanes finally passed [^26]. Clark, demonstrating a commendable (or perhaps foolhardy) commitment, personally bore the expense of repairing and restoring all the damaged homes [^7] [^31]. During this same challenging year, road-builder Finley Smith initiated plans to extend Broward Boulevard, a vital artery, from State Road 7 all the way to the Holloway Canal [^32] [^26].

In 1948, Chauncey Clark Jr.'s residence became the first to be completed, and he, along with his family, promptly moved in [^26]. Construction operations expanded, supported by a dedicated sales group, leading to the completion and sale of approximately three houses per week [^26]. By the end of that year, an estimated 120 homes had been built [^17], and the city's population swelled to a modest 30 families [^26]. A notable demographic event occurred when Ann Carter, wife of Claude E. Carter, gave birth to Eugene Carter, marking him as the first child born within the nascent city limits [^17] [^31] [^7]. The year 1948 also saw the completion of new dikes and a crucial pumping station on the East Holloway Canal [^26], and the formal establishment of The Plantation Community Church, which held its inaugural services in Frederick Peters' rather humble construction trailer office [^7].

However, the relentless forces of nature were not yet finished with Plantation. In September and October 1948, two more hurricanes impacted the area, once again causing widespread flooding and, during the second storm, the unfortunate breakage of a dike still very much under construction [^26] [^17]. Swift repairs and extensions to the dikes, along with the deployment of new [cofferdams](/Cofferdam) and continuous pumping, were employed to finally stem the flooding [^26]. Despite these heroic efforts, house sales understandably ground to a halt in 1949 due to the persistent and disheartening cycle of inundation. Although work continued on new roads, dikes, and houses, Clark's Plantation Homes Inc. was eventually dissolved, its assets reverting to Frederick C. Peters [^26].

The year 1949 also marked the opening of Plantation Pumping Station No. 2, a significant infrastructure improvement capable of pumping an impressive 126 million gallons of water per day into the North New River Canal [^7]. Socially, it saw the founding of the Plantation Women's Club by Mrs. Helen Hoffman [^31] [^7], and the establishment of the Plantation Homeowners' organization by Dr. Abram Hoffman [^7]. At this point, the community consisted of 40 occupied homes, a small but determined cluster of residents [^7].

Then, in 1950, the Plantation Golf Course and Country Club was completed, built with the rather strategic intent of encouraging the westward extension of Broward Boulevard, further connecting the fledgling community [^33] [^7].

### City incorporation (1953–1963)

The city of Plantation finally achieved its official status, being incorporated as a city on April 23, 1953 [^27] [^34]. At the time of its formal inception, the city boasted a modest population of 300 souls [^28] and operated on a shoestring budget that barely scraped past $2,000 [^7]. A sum that, even then, likely bought little more than good intentions and a few shovels. The Plantation Homeowners Association appointed Ellsworth D. Gage, then its president, as the city's very first Mayor. Paul Stoner, Winslow Freeman, George Bartold, Walter Bartels, and Wilfred J. Perry Lohman were elected to the inaugural City Council [^7]. Notably, none of these early city officials drew any salary from their positions, a testament to their civic dedication (or perhaps the sheer lack of funds) [^7]. A building originally envisioned as a community center, but at the time serving the more utilitarian purpose of a warehouse, was pressed into service for the first city council meeting, doubling as city hall, fire station, and police station. This structure, initially known as the Hoffman Building, now forms the kitchen area of the Deicke Auditorium [^35] [^36] [^7]. A humble beginning, indeed.

On August 1, 1954, the Miami Herald, with a flair for the dramatic, publicly unveiled the city plan, boldly proclaiming Plantation "The City of the Future" [^28]. A rather optimistic forecast for a place still finding its footing.

In 1955, S. Robinson Estey was elected as the city's second mayor, and notably, the first to be elected to the position by popular vote [^7]. The Plantation Police Department was formally organized in the same year, with its inaugural police car and officer, Henry C. 'Hank' Donath. Donath, a man of singular dedication, effectively ran the entire department alone for several years, remaining on call 24 hours a day [^33] [^37]. At this point, the city's population remained a quaint less than 800 people [^31].

The city's fire department's annual barbecue fundraiser, a tradition that commenced in 1956, has proven to be remarkably enduring, remaining one of Plantation's cherished annual traditions to this day [^7] [^38]. The Plantation's Volunteer Fire Department was subsequently formed in 1957, with Richard Stephenson appointed as its first Fire Chief [^7]. The city's first industrial plant, Airpax Products, Co., opened its doors on Sunrise Boulevard in 1957, in what is now known as Plantation Technology Park [^7]. This year also saw the completion of Plantation Community Church's first dedicated sanctuary (now known as Missions Prayer Chapel) [^7] and the opening of the Sunshine State Parkway, a vital artery now more commonly referred to as [Florida's Turnpike](/Florida%27s_Turnpike), which provided a crucial connection between Miami and Fort Pierce, [Florida](/Florida) [^39]. By 1958, construction of the permanent City Hall was finally completed [^33]. A dedicated fire station was also built on Broward Boulevard, and Frederick T. Peters, son of the city's founder, Frederick C. Peters, was appointed as the city's fire chief [^28].

Plantation's budget, a reliable indicator of growth, had expanded to over $170,000 by 1959 [^7]. That year, the city's first school was proudly dedicated: Berenice Todd Peters Elementary School, named in honor of the wife of city founder Frederick C. Peters (and known today simply as Peters Elementary). This substantial institution, boasting 24 classrooms and designed to accommodate 725 children, was constructed on a generous 10-acre parcel of land donated by Frederick Peters himself [^33] [^7]. Hank Donath, the aforementioned lone officer, was formally appointed as the city's first police chief, with the operational costs of the police department rather ingeniously covered by cigarette taxes [^7].

In 1960, the city, perhaps still clinging to its aspirational identity, officially adopted the slogan "The Dream City," complete with matching license plates [^7]. A nice touch, if a little on the nose.

The Plantation Library, initially operating out of Peters Elementary School, was founded in 1961, with Helen B. Hoffman serving as chairwoman and dedicated members of the Plantation Woman's Club volunteering their time and efforts [^7]. In 1962, Edwin Deicke made a significant philanthropic contribution, donating $100,000 to the city for the expansion and renovation of the Hoffman Building, which would later be renamed the Deicke Auditorium in 1973 in his honor [^31]. The same year also witnessed the founding of the city's chamber of commerce and the opening of the Doctors General Hospital, further solidifying the community's infrastructure [^7].

By 1963, the city's population had reached a respectable 8,500 [^17]. It was also in this year that its original motto, "From the Wilderness, This City," was formally made official, accompanied by the adoption of a corresponding city seal. The seal, a creation of Mayor Robinson Estey and architect A.T. Hardel, was later discovered to contain a spelling error in its Latin translation. However, future mayor Frank Veltri, in a decision that speaks volumes about tradition (or perhaps bureaucratic inertia), chose not to correct it [^40]. The city's community center, a structure designed by the original city master plan architect [Russell Pancoast](/Russell_Pancoast), was also built in 1963, becoming the new home for the city's first library, which had outgrown its humble beginnings at Peters Elementary [^41] [^7].

### Gulfstream developments (1964–1979)

Following the passing of Frederick C. Peters in July 1964, his family made a significant strategic decision, selling a vast 5,400 acres (22 km^2^) of undeveloped land situated to the west of University Drive (an artery originally, and rather charmingly, named Annapu Road [^42] [^28]). This substantial parcel was acquired for approximately $3,000 per acre by the Gulfstream Land Development Company, under the leadership of its president, John H. Cleary [^28] [^7]. The primary objective behind this acquisition was the ambitious development of the Jacaranda community, a project conceived with the grand intent of constructing an equivalent to the refined, Mediterranean-revival aesthetic and upscale ambiance of [Coral Gables](/Coral_Gables,_Florida) within the less established confines of [Broward County](/Broward_County,_Florida) [^7].

Other significant expansions and additions characterized this period of growth. These included the establishment of Plantation Elementary School in 1965 [^7], the Florida Air Academy in 1969 [^7], Plantation High School (the city's first dedicated high school) [^33] [^7], and Plantation General Hospital, which, upon its opening in 1966, was a substantial 264-bed facility [^43] [^33]. The telecommunications giant [Motorola](/Motorola) also established a facility in the city in 1969 [^7], signaling a shift towards a more diversified economic base.

By 1970, Plantation's population had swelled to 23,523 [^44], a clear indicator of its accelerating development. In 1972, a construction bid totaling $1.03 million was accepted for a new city hall, a much-needed upgrade, and groundbreaking commenced for the construction of the Deicke Auditorium [^33].

Plantation Acres, a distinct area specifically designated as a Special Public Interest Rural District to protect its natural landscape and character [^28] [^45], along with Melaleuca Isles, were formally annexed into Plantation in 1973 [^7]. The Deicke Auditorium and the new, modern Plantation City Hall were both dedicated in May and December of that year, respectively [^7] [^33]. Also in 1973, the Gulfstream consortium completed its acquisition of the remaining land holdings from the Peters family. Moving decisively away from Plantation's original, more rural aspirations, Gulfstream pivoted its focus towards attracting commercial, industrial, and home office establishments. This strategic shift led to significant agreements with major corporations such as [Motorola](/Motorola), [American Express](/American_Express), and the developers who would eventually construct the [Broward Mall](/Westfield_Broward) [^28]. The Plantation Historical Society, dedicated to preserving the city's evolving story, was founded the following year by Genevieve Veltri, Dorothy O'Hare, Lois Brickhouse, and Marilyn King. Their inaugural meeting was held in the Veltri home, with Genevieve Veltri elected as the first president [^7] [^31] [^46].

Frank Veltri was first elected as the city's mayor in 1975, embarking on what would become an extraordinarily long and impactful tenure. Veltri ultimately became the city's longest-serving mayor, completing an impressive six terms over 24 years [^7]. In the same year, the financial services behemoth [American Express](/American_Express) relocated its 'Southern Region Operations Center' to a newly constructed building in Plantation, commencing operations with an initial workforce of 1,000 employees [^47] [^48].

During the [US bicentennial](/United_States_Bicentennial) celebrations in 1976, a majestic 45-foot oak tree was ceremoniously planted in Plantation's Fifth Street Park, serving as a symbolic representation of the historic [Liberty Tree](/Liberty_Tree). Consequently, the park was fittingly renamed Liberty Tree Park [^7]. In 1977, the city and [Broward County](/Broward_County,_Florida) jointly acquired land that had previously been a part of the Peters family farm, initiating work on the Plantation Heritage Park with the aid of a grant from the [Land and Water Conservation Fund](/Land_and_Water_Conservation_Fund) [^7].

The [Broward Mall](/Westfield_Broward) opened its doors in 1978, occupying what had once been simple cow pasture land. At the time of its grand opening, it held the distinction of being the largest mall in the Southern United States, a sprawling retail complex encompassing 1 million square feet [^49] [^7]. The year 1978 also marked the city's [silver anniversary](/Silver_jubilee), a milestone celebrated with three days of festive events, including the ceremonial burying of a [time capsule](/Time_capsule) intended to be updated every 25 years [^7]. One can only imagine what future generations will make of its contents.

In 1979, the Florida Air Academy ceased operations, and its land was subsequently sold to the Jewish Community Center [^7].

A rather intriguing historical footnote from this period involves the mobster [John Roselli](/John_Roselli) (born 1905), a notorious liaison and [fixer](/Fixer_(person)) for the infamous [Chicago Outfit](/Chicago_Outfit) with ties to Hollywood, Los Angeles, and the Las Vegas Strip. His final known residence, until June 28, 1976, was at his sister Enid and brother-in-law Joseph Daigle's home at 5220 SW 10th Court in Plantation. Roselli's murdered body was discovered in a steel drum in Dumfoundling Bay in Miami on August 9 of that year [^50] [^51] [^52]. A grim reminder that even in a burgeoning "Dream City," certain realities persist.

### Recent history (1980–present)

By 1980, Plantation's population had swelled to 48,653 [^44], a clear indication of its continued growth. This year also marked the city's first designation as a 'Tree City' by the esteemed [Arbor Day Foundation](/Arbor_Day_Foundation) [^7] [^53]. A small, green victory in the face of relentless development, one might say. The Plantation Library, a vital community resource, was fittingly renamed the Helen B. Hoffman Plantation Library in the following year, honoring a key figure in its establishment [^31].

In 1983, the city proudly unveiled Plantation Central Park, a sprawling 77-acre recreation complex. This impressive facility boasted an Olympic-sized swimming pool, a gymnasium, and dedicated spaces for softball, football, soccer, tennis, and basketball, catering to a wide array of community athletic pursuits [^7]. The same year saw an attempt to repurpose the former Plantation Chamber of Commerce, a modest 1,000-square-foot office building, by moving it over a mile by truck to a new location. The intent was for this building to serve as a museum for the Plantation Historical Society. However, in a rather unfortunate turn of events, it was vandalized and subsequently fell from its foundation, necessitating its eventual demolition [^7]. Instead, an alternative, purpose-built Plantation Historical Museum, founded by the indefatigable Genevieve Veltri, was dedicated in June 1985 [^31] [^7].

The city's landscape department, ever keen on fostering civic pride and greenery, established the Plantation Landscaping Award for Nurturing our Town (PLANT) awards in 1984. These awards, developed as part of the [Tree City USA](/Arbor_Day_Foundation) program, aimed to recognize and reward outstanding landscaping and maintenance efforts throughout the community [^7]. The same year also saw the initial public opening of the Plantation Heritage Park, providing residents with another valuable green space [^7].

In 1988, a mere decade after the grand opening of the [Broward Mall](/Westfield_Broward), the city witnessed the opening of two additional, substantial shopping malls. The Fountains Shopping Mall, a 450,000-square-foot complex, represented a $60 million investment, while the Fashion Mall at Plantation, even larger at 660,000 square feet, featured prominent anchor stores like Macy's and Lord & Taylor [^54] [^7]. The retail landscape, it seemed, was booming.

The population continued its upward trajectory, reaching 66,116 by 1990 [^44]. The following year, Plantation's PLANT awards bestowed special recognition upon [Marjory Stoneman Douglas](/Marjory_Stoneman_Douglas), then a venerable 100 years of age, honoring her as the "First Lady of Conservation" for her tireless and invaluable efforts to preserve the precious [Everglades](/Everglades) [^7]. A well-deserved accolade for a woman who understood the true value of the wilderness.

The insurance company Kemper National Services first established operations in Plantation in 1993. The following year, it announced ambitious plans to double its office space within the city and hire up to 800 additional employees, signaling strong economic growth. At this time, the city's largest employers were [American Express](/American_Express), followed closely by [Motorola](/Motorola) [^55].

During the 100th anniversary of the modern [Olympic Games](/Olympic_Games) in 1996, the symbolic relay run of the [Olympic Flame](/Olympic_flame) passed directly through Plantation city center, a moment of international recognition [^56]. In September of that year, a fire at the [Plantation Towne Mall](/Plantation_Towne_Mall) became the city's largest fire to date, impacting a significant 56,000 square feet of the mall's structure [^57] [^7]. Following this destructive event, the area was rebuilt and rebranded as Plantation Towne Square, featuring a new [Publix](/Publix) supermarket as its anchor store, demonstrating the city's resilience [^7].

The [2000 census](/2000_United_States_census) recorded the city's population at 82,934, representing a diverse tapestry of 15 distinct ethnic groups [^58]. New city developments and enhancements during this period included the 11,500-square-foot (1,070 m^2^) Volunteer Park Community Center (1999), the tranquil Park East Multicultural Garden (2001), the convenient Community Bus Service (2001), the Jim Ward 16,000 sq ft (1,500 m^2^) Community Center (2002), the Jack Carter Harmony Park (2002), the Happy Tails Dog Park (2002), the Plantation Equestrian Center (2005), and the impressive Plantation Preserve Golf Course and Club (2006) [^7]. A veritable explosion of civic amenities.

Plantation celebrated its 50-year [golden anniversary](/Golden_jubilee) in 2003, commemorating the milestone with a week-long celebration and the ceremonial updating of the city's time capsule [^7].

[Hurricane Wilma](/Hurricane_Wilma) made its unwelcome presence felt in Plantation on Monday, October 24, 2005, causing extensive damage and widespread power outages [^7]. The significant damage wrought by the hurricane ultimately led to the subsequent closure of the Fashion Mall in 2006 [^59]. Nature, it seems, has a way of reminding us of our impermanence.

In 2007, the [Broward Mall](/Westfield_Broward) was acquired by the [Westfield Group](/Westfield_Group), undergoing a multimillion-dollar renovation and subsequently being rebranded as [Westfield Broward](/Westfield_Broward) [^7].

The city earned recognition as one of the nation's "100 Best Communities for Young People" by [America's Promise Alliance](/America%27s_Promise_Alliance) in 2008 [^60]. This accolade was repeated in subsequent years, including 2010 [^61] and 2011 [^62], indicating a consistent commitment to its younger residents.

The [2010 census](/2010_United_States_census) reported the city's population at 84,955 people [^63]. During this year, the vacant former Fashion Mall, a casualty of Hurricane Wilma, was slated for auction. However, the auction was abruptly canceled after the property owner settled a court judgment [^64] [^65]. The drama, it seems, continued even for unoccupied retail spaces.

In 2011, Diane Veltri Bendekovic, daughter of the long-serving former mayor Frank Veltri, was elected as mayor of the city, bringing a touch of dynastic continuity to local governance [^66] [^67].

The city's 60th anniversary in 2013 was marked by the publication of a new book dedicated to its rich history: *Images of America: Plantation* [^7]. A fitting tribute to six decades of evolution.

The developers of the previously closed Fashion Mall eventually filed for bankruptcy in October 2014. The property was subsequently sold in a bankruptcy auction in April 2015 for $37.7 million [^68]. Demolition of the long-vacant former Fashion Mall commenced in 2016, carefully preserving the existing hotel, office, and parking areas. This cleared the way for [Plantation Walk](/Plantation_Walk) (a project previously known as 321 North [^68]), an ambitious $350 million complex designed to include 700 apartments, 200,000 square feet of retail and restaurants, and remodeled versions of the existing 160,000-square-foot office tower and [Sheraton hotel](/Sheraton_Hotels_and_Resorts) [^69] [^70] [^71]. In September 2018, a settlement was finally reached, resolving legal conflicts between the area's bankruptcy trustee and other parties previously involved in the redevelopment. The project was targeting completion in 2021 [^68] [^72].

The [American Express](/American_Express) office in Plantation closed its doors in 2017 when the company relocated to a new facility in neighboring Sunrise, [Florida](/Florida) [^73]. In response to this significant corporate departure, committee review began on 'Plantation Midtown,' a new 25-acre (0.10 km^2^) [mixed-use development](/Mixed-use_development) envisioned for the site of the former American Express office [^74]. Adapt or perish, as they say in the world of urban planning.

On July 6, 2019, a rather dramatic and unfortunate incident occurred: 23 people were injured, two seriously, by a gas explosion at the Market on University shopping plaza on South University Drive. The blast caused extensive damage to the plaza and nearby buildings [^75]. Investigations later revealed that the explosion was caused by People's Gas, a division of [TECO Energy](/TECO_Energy), failing to properly close and lock a gas line after a customer request dating back to December 2018, a clear violation of both Federal and [Florida](/Florida) law [^76]. A stark reminder that even the most mundane infrastructure can harbor significant risks.

In June 2020, in the wake of the [George Floyd protests](/George_Floyd_protests) and a broader national reckoning with historical nomenclature, some residents called for the city, along with certain local schools whose names include the word "plantation," to be renamed. This was due to the undeniable connotation of the word "plantation" with [slavery in the American South](/Slavery_in_the_United_States). While the city's name has no direct links to slavery, the debate highlighted the evolving sensitivities around language and history. Other residents, predictably, expressed their opposition to renaming, citing tradition and the city's unique origins [^77] [^78]. A debate that, like many, is more about perception than objective truth.

In 2021, the [Westfield Mall](/Westfield_Group) reverted to its previous, more familiar name of Broward Mall, following the dissolution of the [Westfield Group](/Westfield_Group). Some things, it seems, are destined to come full circle.

## Geography

An [East-facing aerial photo of Plantation. Flamingo Road (bottom) separates Plantation from [Sunrise](/Sunrise,_Florida).](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c5/Plantation_aerial_view.jpg/300px-Plantation_aerial_view.jpg) offers a clear perspective of the city's layout and its proximity to its neighbors.

### Land size

As of the [2010 census](/2010_United_States_census), the city encompassed a total area of 21.93 square miles (57 km^2^). Of this, 21.74 square miles (56 km^2^) constitutes land, while a persistent 0.19 square miles (0 km^2^), or approximately 0.87%, remains water [^79]. A small but significant portion, given its history.

### Location and surroundings

Plantation is strategically situated in central [Broward County](/Broward_County,_Florida), a position that places it within a dynamic network of neighboring municipalities. It is bordered by [Lauderhill](/Lauderhill,_Florida) to its northeast, [Sunrise](/Sunrise,_Florida) to both its north and west, [Davie](/Davie,_Florida) to the south, and the more bustling [Fort Lauderdale](/Fort_Lauderdale,_Florida) to its east. A rather central location, considering its origins.

### Climate

Plantation experiences a [tropical rainforest climate](/Tropical_rainforest_climate) (Af), hovering on the very edge of a [tropical monsoon climate](/Tropical_monsoon_climate) (Am). This subtle distinction arises from the precipitation levels in December, the driest month, which are just shy of the 60mm threshold that formally separates these two categories. One might even call it a perpetual state of damp anticipation.

On average, August, with its oppressive humidity, registers as the hottest month, boasting an average high of 90.0 °F (32.2 °C). In stark contrast, January offers a brief respite, standing as the coolest month with an average low of 57.0 °F (13.9 °C). However, even [Florida](/Florida) can surprise, as evidenced by a record low of 28.0 °F (−2.2 °C) [^80]. A reminder that even paradise has its cold snaps.

