### Households

As of the [2020 US census](/2020_United_States_census), the city was home to 91,750 individuals, comprising 34,532 households, and within those, 22,738 families [^90]. A bustling collection of interconnected lives.

Rewinding a decade, the [2010 US census](/2010_United_States_census) indicated a population of 84,955 people, distributed among 34,211 households, with 22,156 identified as families residing within the city limits [^91].

Also in 2010, a significant 66.0% of the 34,190 total households were classified as family households, with 47.7% specifically being husband-wife households. A notable 28.5% of households included at least one child under the age of 18 years, ensuring a certain level of youthful exuberance (or chaos, depending on your perspective). On the other side of the spectrum, 26.3% of all households consisted of individual householders living alone, and a more modest 8.3% featured someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was measured at 2.47 individuals, while the average family unit was slightly larger, at 3.01 members [^63].

### Age and gender

As of 2010, the median age of Plantation's population was 39.7 years, a figure suggesting a fairly balanced demographic. The age distribution revealed that 23.5% of residents were 19 years or younger, with 21.5% specifically under the age of 18. The working-age population, those from 20 to 39 years, accounted for 26.9%. The 40 to 59 age bracket represented 30.0%, while those from 60 to 84 years comprised 17.5%. A small but significant 2.1% of the population was 85 years or older, a testament to longevity (or perhaps just the persistent good weather). [^63].

In terms of gender, the 2010 data showed that the population was 52.6% female overall, with women comprising an even larger proportion, 53.5%, of the population aged over 18 years [^63].

### Employment and income

According to a 2013–2017 [American Community Survey](/American_Community_Survey) estimate, the [per capita income](/Per_capita_income) for Plantation (when adjusted for [inflation](/Real_versus_nominal_value_(economics)) to 2017 dollars) was $35,897. The median household income stood at $69,531, and the median family income reached $78,839 [^63]. These figures suggest a comfortable, if not extravagant, economic standing for many residents. The median earnings for a full-time, year-round male worker were $54,188, a figure that unfortunately still outpaced the $44,537 earned by their female counterparts [^63]. Some disparities, it seems, are rather slow to disappear.

Between 2013 and 2017, the estimate also identified 9.0% of the city's overall population (and 6.7% of its families) living below the established [poverty line](/Poverty_threshold). This included 11.8% of those under the age of 18, a particularly vulnerable demographic, and 5.2% of those aged 65 or over, suggesting that even in retirement, financial security is not always guaranteed [^63].

In terms of occupational distribution for civilians aged 16 and older, the largest sector between 2013 and 2017 was in management, business, science, and arts occupations, accounting for a significant 43.4% of the workforce. This was closely followed by sales and office occupations, which comprised 28.9% [^63]. A city, it seems, that values both intellectual pursuits and the art of the deal.

### Language

As of the [2000 census](/2000_United_States_census), the distribution of first languages spoken within the city showcased a diverse linguistic landscape. [English](/English_language) remained the dominant language at 78.01%, followed by [Spanish](/Spanish_language) at 13.00%, reflecting the strong Hispanic influence in South [Florida](/Florida). Other languages spoken included [French Creole](/Haitian_Creole) (2.24%), [French](/French_language) (1.31%), [Hebrew](/Hebrew_language) (0.72%), [Portuguese](/Portuguese_language) (0.72%), [Italian](/Italian_language) (0.59%), [German](/German_language) (0.55%), and [Arabic](/Arabic_language) (0.46%). The remaining 2.40% encompassed a fascinating array of "all others" [^92]. A truly cosmopolitan cacophony, if one were to listen closely.

## Economy

A 2012 survey of business owners within Plantation identified a substantial total of 13,674 companies operating within the city limits [^93] [^63]. This robust entrepreneurial ecosystem underscores the city's economic vitality. An [economic census](/United_States_Economic_Census), also conducted in 2012, further determined that total retail sales within the city amounted to a significant $1.72 billion [^93]. Clearly, the residents of Plantation appreciate a good shopping experience.

Specific companies that currently maintain operations within Plantation include [DHL](/DHL), which houses its Express Head Office for the [United States](/United_States) here [^94], the [University of Phoenix](/University_of_Phoenix) with its South [Florida](/Florida) Campus [^95], and [TradeStation](/TradeStation), a notable presence in the financial technology sector [^96]. However, the corporate landscape is, as ever, subject to change. Companies that once called Plantation home include [American Express](/American_Express), which operated here from 1975 until 2017 [^48] [^73], and [Motorola](/Motorola), whose presence spanned from 1969 to 2015 [^7] [^97]. A reminder that even the most established presences can be transient.

### Malls

For a time, Plantation was a veritable hub for retail therapy, boasting two significant shopping malls situated directly across the street from one another. To the south of Broward Boulevard stood the [Westfield Broward Mall](/Westfield_Broward), a testament to traditional retail architecture [^49]. Directly opposite, to the north of Broward Boulevard, was the Fashion Mall [^7]. However, the capricious tides of commerce and the unforgiving wrath of [Hurricane Wilma](/Hurricane_Wilma) intervened, leading to the closure of the Fashion Mall in 2006. It is currently undergoing a rather extensive transformation, being re-developed as part of the ambitious Plantation Walk project [^59] [^68]. A phoenix, perhaps, from the ashes of retail obsolescence.

### Golf and country clubs

The city of Plantation, despite its watery origins, has cultivated a rather impressive array of golf and country clubs, a testament to the human desire to impose manicured greens upon the wild. The oldest club within the city's geographical embrace is the expansive 293-acre Fort Lauderdale Country Club, which, rather remarkably, was first founded in 1926. Its establishment, however, was swiftly followed by the rather inconvenient setback caused by the devastating [1926 Miami hurricane](/1926_Miami_hurricane) [^98] [^99] [^100]. When it initially opened, this 6,661-yard course was known simply as the West Side Golf Course and was owned by the city of [Fort Lauderdale](/Fort_Lauderdale,_Florida) [^101]. Its name was changed in December 1928 when it was leased by [Fort Lauderdale](/Fort_Lauderdale,_Florida) [^101]. In 1951, the club underwent a significant expansion, adding a second 18-hole, 6,915-yard 'North Course' [^102] [^103]. Although initially a public club, it transitioned to a private establishment in 1957 when it was sold by the city of [Fort Lauderdale](/Fort_Lauderdale,_Florida) [^101]. The club's original 'South Course' was a collaborative design by Joseph A. Roseman, Hebert Charles Tippet, and George Richardson Sr. [^104] [^101], and has since been thoughtfully re-designed by Charles Ankrom (in 1991) and Kipp Schulties (in 2006) [^101] [^105]. The North Course, for its part, was designed by Robert 'Red' F. Lawrence [^106], and subsequently re-designed by Tom Pearson (in 1999) and Kipp Schulties (in 2006) [^107].

The first club not directly owned by [Fort Lauderdale](/Fort_Lauderdale,_Florida), the Plantation Golf Course and Country Club, was a collaborative design effort by Robert 'Red' F. Lawrence and the original city master plan architect, [Russell Pancoast](/Russell_Pancoast), opening its greens in 1950 [^7]. A particularly poignant detail emerged during its construction: the discovery of a [Native American](/Native_Americans_in_the_United_States) [burial mound](/Tumulus) on the site of what would become the 14th hole. In a respectful nod to the area's original [Seminole](/Seminole) and [Tequesta](/Tequesta) residents, each hole on the course was subsequently given a distinct Native American name [^33] [^7]. Beyond the golf course, the club offered a swimming pool, tennis courts, and a clubhouse, catering to a broader range of leisure activities [^7].

Another of the city's exclusive private golf courses is the 162-acre Lago Mar Country Club, a name that, for the avoidance of confusion, should not be mistaken for the more famously opulent [Mar-a-Lago](/Mar-a-Lago) [^99]. Established in 1969 [^108], Lago Mar was acquired from its original builders in 1980 and subsequently underwent a comprehensive re-design in 2009 by Kipp Schulties [^109], reopening to much fanfare on January 1, 2010 [^110]. The club features teeing grounds ranging from 5,811 to 6,756 yards and offers other amenities such as private tennis courts, catering to a discerning clientele [^111] [^112].

[Plantation Preserve Golf Course & Club in July 2024](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c5/Plantation_Preserve_Golf_Course_%26_Club_in_July_2024.jpg/300px-Plantation_Preserve_Golf_Course_%26_Club_in_July_2024.jpg) shows the modern face of golf in the city.

Yet another public, though privately owned, club within the city is the Jacaranda Golf Club. This impressive 285-acre, 7,247-yard course was initially designed by Mark Mahannah and constructed in 1970, then thoughtfully redesigned by [Bobby Weed](/Bobby_Weed) in 2006 [^99] [^113] [^114].

Work on a new city-owned golf course commenced in 2002 when the city wisely purchased the property of the original Plantation Golf Course. This acquisition paved the way for the ambitious new 'Plantation Preserve' development. This extensive development work culminated in the creation of the Plantation Preserve Golf Course and Club: a magnificent 214-acre, 7,148-yard course, meticulously designed by [Robert von Hagge](/Robert_von_Hagge), Michael Smelek, and Rick Baril, which was proudly dedicated in April 2006 [^7] [^99] [^115]. A fitting addition to a city that clearly appreciates its greens.

