## Media

Plantation is an integrated part of the larger Miami-Fort Lauderdale-Hollywood media market, a sprawling informational ecosystem that, for those keeping score, ranks as the sixteenth largest media market [^121], the eleventh largest radio market [^122], and the sixteenth largest television market [^123] in the [United States](/United_States). So, while you might feel tucked away, the news will still find you.

The city's primary daily newspapers, providing the essential local narratives and broader regional news, are the [South Florida Sun-Sentinel](/South_Florida_Sun-Sentinel) and [The Miami Herald](/The_Miami_Herald). For the Spanish-speaking population, their equally vital counterparts are [El Sentinel](/El_Sentinel_del_Sur_de_la_Florida) and [El Nuevo Herald](/El_Nuevo_Herald).

Beyond the printed word, Plantation has also served as a backdrop for the silver screen, lending its distinctive character to feature films. Notably, the iconic 1980 comedy [Caddyshack](/Caddyshack) utilized the Plantation Country Club for its memorable pool scenes [^124]. Years later, in 1998, the film [There's Something About Mary](/There%27s_Something_About_Mary) famously used Plantation City Hall, located at 400 NW 73rd Avenue, to stand in for the film's high school [^125]. A rather amusing, if slightly ironic, transformation for a municipal building.

